# Plan: Add `mistral-instruct-v3` Specialized Chat Template Handler

## Context

llama.cpp's `common/chat.cpp` has a specialized template dispatch system (`common_chat_try_specialized_template`) that inspects a model's Jinja template source string and routes to hand-written PEG-parser-based handlers for formats that are hard to auto-parse. The existing "Ministral 3" handler targets Mistral's reasoning models that use `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`, `[TOOL_CALLS]`, and `[ARGS]` markers.

Mistral Instruct v0.3 (e.g., Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.3) is a simpler format: user turns are wrapped in `[INST]…[/INST]`, system messages are prepended inside the first `[INST]` block (no `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` tag), and assistant turns are followed by `</s>`. No existing specialized handler covers this format. Currently such templates fall through to the generic autoparser; a dedicated handler ensures correct, reliable parsing.

**Constraint:** Only add new code. Do not modify any existing handler functions or any header files.

---

## Files to Touch

| Action | File | Purpose |
|--------|------|---------|
| **Create** | `models/templates/mistralai-Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.3.jinja` | Reference Jinja template for detection & tests |
| **Add code** | `common/chat.cpp` | New handler function + detection block |
| **Add code** | `tests/test-chat.cpp` | Test cases for the new handler |

---

## Step-by-Step Implementation

### Step 1 — Create the Jinja Template

**File:** `models/templates/mistralai-Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.3.jinja`

This template encodes the official Mistral Instruct v0.3 format and doubles as the detection target.

```jinja
{%- if messages[0]['role'] == 'system' %}
    {%- set system_message = messages[0]['content'] %}
    {%- set loop_messages = messages[1:] %}
{%- else %}
    {%- set loop_messages = messages %}
{%- endif %}
{{- bos_token }}
{%- for message in loop_messages %}
    {%- if message['role'] == 'user' %}
        {%- if loop.first and system_message is defined %}
            {{- '[INST] ' + system_message + '\n\n' + message['content'] + ' [/INST]' }}
        {%- else %}
            {{- '[INST] ' + message['content'] + ' [/INST]' }}
        {%- endif %}
    {%- elif message['role'] == 'assistant' %}
        {{- ' ' + message['content'] + '</s>' }}
    {%- endif %}
{%- endfor %}
```

Key detection signals present in this template:
- `[/INST]` — present (Mistral instruct marker)
- `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` — **absent** (distinguishes from Ministral-3 and v7)
- `[TOOL_CALLS]` — **absent** (distinguishes from Nemo/Ministral tool templates)

### Step 2 — Add the Handler Function

**File:** `common/chat.cpp`  
**Insertion point:** Before `namespace workaround {` (currently line 1519, right after `common_chat_params_init_gigachat_v3` ends at line 1517).

```cpp
static common_chat_params common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(
        const common_chat_template &          tmpl,
        const autoparser::generation_params & inputs) {
    common_chat_params data;

    data.prompt            = common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl(tmpl, inputs);
    data.format            = COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_PEG_NATIVE;
    data.supports_thinking = false;

    auto parser = build_chat_peg_parser([&](common_chat_peg_builder & p) {
        // Simple content-only parser: capture all output after generation prompt
        return p.literal(inputs.generation_prompt) + p.content(p.rest());
    });

    data.parser = parser.save();

    return data;
}
```

**Rationale for simplicity:** Mistral Instruct v0.3 basic format emits plain text content followed by the EOS token `</s>` (handled by the inference engine's stop-token logic). No special preserved tokens, no reasoning blocks, no in-band tool calls — so the PEG parser only needs to capture `rest()`.

### Step 3 — Register with Auto-Detection

**File:** `common/chat.cpp`  
**Insertion point:** Inside `common_chat_try_specialized_template()`, immediately after the closing brace of the existing Ministral-3 block (line 1644), before the GPT-OSS check.

```cpp
// Mistral Instruct v3 - [INST]/[/INST] format with system message prepended to first user turn
// Distinguishes from Ministral 3 by the absence of [SYSTEM_PROMPT]
if (src.find("[/INST]") != std::string::npos &&
    src.find("[SYSTEM_PROMPT]") == std::string::npos &&
    src.find("[TOOL_CALLS]") == std::string::npos) {
    LOG_DBG("Using specialized template: Mistral Instruct v3\n");
    return common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(tmpl, params);
}
```

**Why these three conditions:**
| Condition | Reason |
|-----------|--------|
| `[/INST]` present | Positively identifies Mistral instruct-family templates |
| `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` absent | Excludes Ministral-3 (caught earlier) and v7/Devstral templates |
| `[TOOL_CALLS]` absent | Excludes Nemo and other tool-capable Mistral variants that need different handling |

**Ordering guarantee:** The Ministral-3 block (lines 1640–1644) is checked first and requires `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`; the new block can never incorrectly match a Ministral-3 template.

### Step 4 — Add Tests

**File:** `tests/test-chat.cpp`  
**Insertion point:** After the closing `}` of the Ministral-3 test block (currently line 1770).

```cpp
{
    // Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.3
    auto tst = peg_tester("models/templates/mistralai-Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.3.jinja", detailed_debug);

    tst.test("Hello, world!\nWhat's up?").expect(message_assist).expect_reconstruction().run();
}
```

`message_assist` and `expect_reconstruction()` are already defined in the test harness (used by Ministral-3 tests immediately above) — no new infrastructure required.

---

## Critical Files Reference

| File | Key lines |
|------|-----------|
| `common/chat.cpp` | Handler function: insert at ~1518 (before `namespace workaround`) |
| `common/chat.cpp` | Detection: insert at ~1644 (after Ministral-3 block, before GPT-OSS block) |
| `common/chat.cpp` | `common_chat_try_specialized_template()` starts at line 1634 |
| `common/chat.cpp` | Ministral-3 handler reference: lines 825–940 |
| `common/chat.cpp` | GigaChat v3 handler (simple handler reference): lines 1446–1517 |
| `tests/test-chat.cpp` | Ministral-3 tests: lines 1698–1770 (insert new block after line 1770) |
| `src/llama-chat.h` | **Do not touch** — header file constraint |
| `src/llama-chat.cpp` | **Do not touch** — existing legacy handlers |

---

## Verification

1. **Build:** `cmake -B build && cmake --build build --target test-chat --parallel`
2. **Run tests:** `./build/bin/test-chat` — all existing tests must still pass; the new Mistral Instruct v3 test must also pass
3. **Manual smoke test:** Pass the template file directly to the test binary with the `--template` flag to observe prompt rendering and PEG parser output
4. **Non-regression check:** Confirm that the Ministral-3 test block (lines 1698–1770) still routes through `common_chat_params_init_ministral_3`, not the new handler — verified by the fact that Ministral-3's template source contains `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` which is caught first

